And this is the general
idea that if you look

00:00:07.361 --> 00:00:09.270
at a organism's genome,

00:00:09.270 --> 00:00:11.259
that not all of the genes are being

00:00:11.259 --> 00:00:14.585
transcribed and translated
at the same time.

00:00:14.585 --> 00:00:17.114
It could actually depend on the type of

00:00:17.114 --> 00:00:19.781
cell that that DNA is inside of,

00:00:21.070 --> 00:00:24.779
or it could depend on the
environment for that organism.

00:00:24.779 --> 00:00:26.811
So for example, if you look at,

00:00:26.811 --> 00:00:29.327
say, a multicellular organism,

00:00:29.327 --> 00:00:31.774
this, maybe this is, and these are

00:00:31.774 --> 00:00:33.882
oversimplifications right over here,

00:00:33.882 --> 00:00:36.978
maybe this is type of immune cell,

00:00:36.978 --> 00:00:37.978
immune cell,

00:00:39.286 --> 00:00:43.450
and let's say that this
over here is a muscle cell,

00:00:43.450 --> 00:00:45.371
and they're not necessarily, or not likely

00:00:45.371 --> 00:00:46.684
to be these perfect circles,

00:00:46.684 --> 00:00:48.300
but this is just for the idea.

00:00:48.300 --> 00:00:51.616
And they're going to
have the exact same DNA.

00:00:51.616 --> 00:00:54.758
So the DNA in both of these is the same.

00:00:54.758 --> 00:00:55.591
So DNA is

00:00:57.556 --> 00:00:58.686
the same

00:00:58.686 --> 00:01:01.008
inside, and these are going to be,

00:01:01.008 --> 00:01:02.123
these are Eukaryotes,

00:01:02.123 --> 00:01:04.159
so I'll draw the nuclear membrane there,

00:01:04.159 --> 00:01:04.992
same DNA.

00:01:06.793 --> 00:01:10.013
But they have very different
roles inside of this organism.

00:01:10.013 --> 00:01:11.819
So it doesn't make sense, in fact,

00:01:11.819 --> 00:01:13.977
