produce different proteins.

00:01:15.702 --> 00:01:19.218
They're gonna have
different enzyme proteins

00:01:19.218 --> 00:01:21.385
inside of their cytoplasm.

00:01:22.702 --> 00:01:26.193
And so DNA regulation, one
way to think about it is,

00:01:26.193 --> 00:01:28.542
well if they have the exact same genome,

00:01:28.542 --> 00:01:31.314
how do they regulate which of those genes

00:01:31.314 --> 00:01:34.451
are being transcribed and then translated

00:01:34.451 --> 00:01:36.068
and which ones aren't?

00:01:36.068 --> 00:01:38.636
And even if you think about
a unicellular organism.

00:01:38.636 --> 00:01:41.489
Right here we have a bacterium.

00:01:41.489 --> 00:01:43.747
And so it's just one cell, but even it

00:01:43.747 --> 00:01:46.771
will not want to transcribe and translate

00:01:46.771 --> 00:01:48.794
all of its genes at the same time.

00:01:48.794 --> 00:01:51.845
For example, this over here,

00:01:51.845 --> 00:01:54.823
so this is its, this is
the bacterial chromosome.

00:01:54.823 --> 00:01:56.802
This right over here might be a gene

00:01:56.802 --> 00:02:01.088
involved in the digestion
of a certain type of food,

00:02:01.088 --> 00:02:02.799
